 <text>
  <front>
   <head>VERSES written in a Lady's Sherlock upon Death.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">MIstaken fair, lay Sherlock by,</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">His doctrine is deceiving;</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">For whilst he teaches us to die,</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">He cheats us of our living.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="2" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">To die's a lesson we shall know</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">Too soon without a master;</l>
     <l n="7" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Then let us only study now</l>
     <l n="8" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">How may we live the faster.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="3" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="9" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">To live's to love, to bless, be blest</l>
     <l n="10" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">With mutual inclination;</l>
     <l n="11" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Share then my ardour in your breast,</l>
     <l n="12" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And kindly meet my passion.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="4" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="13" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">But if thus bless'd I may not live,</l>
     <l n="14" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">And pity you deny,</l>
     <l n="15" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">To me at least your Sherlock give,</l>
     <l n="16" met="-+|-+|-+" line_length="6">'Tis I must learn to die.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
  </body>
